  "text": "Empirical work based on the traditional framework for household borrowing generally confirms the relevance of income, interest rates, and to some extent, of demographics. [CITATION_1] and [CITATION_2] use simple calibrated models based on microdata to show that changes in these variables can to a certain extent explain household indebtedness in the US and UK, respectively. In fact, these models have some features of housing embedded, but still cannot account for actual developments in terms of household borrowing; for example, the rising indebtedness in the US in the presence of high interest rates, lower income growth, and aging population. The findings on the impact of demographics are mixed, as shown by Davies and others (2010) and Coletta and others (2014) .",
